{
  "text": "reported an incidence about 7% [CITATION_1] , the same as Paice et al. [CITATION_2] . This rate may be up to 9% with both transdermal fentanyl and oral Mo [CITATION_3] and up to 40% in patients on longterm methadone treatment [CITATION_4] . The treatment options and possible etiologies will be discussed. Atropine effectively controlled the profuse sweating following IT Mo or fentanyl in this study. The nerve supply of sweat glands is mainly cholinergic [CITATION_5] with a few adrenergic terminals [CITATION_6] . Acetylcholine is the main pre and postganglionic transmitter of the sympathetic nervous supply of the sweat glands [CITATION_7] , and hence the rationale of using atropine as an anticholinergic greatly attenuates or abolishes sweating [CITATION_8] . Atropine suppressed thermal and non-thermal sweating where both types are cholinergic [CITATION_9] . The cholinergic system is also involved in Mo-induced hyperthermia [CITATION_10] .",
